  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Village Empowerment for Sustainable Peace in Darfur</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The level of destruction to property, especially houses, farms, livestock, and communal infrastructure in Darfur constitutes a systematic attack on livelihoods that has rendered populations destitute and undermined their prospects for sustainable return to their places of origin. To address this loss of household assets, livelihoods, and food security, RI&apos;s interventions in Agriculture and Food Security seek to increase the economic self-sufficiency and resilience of conflict-affected communities. RI&apos;s VESP activities are carefully designed to counteract what RI believes are the greatest impediments to food and economic security - namely, the lack of skills and resources, the lack of leadership, and violence.  The Agricultural Extensionist Program improving organic farming techniques to increase crop yield and farmland sustainability. The AEs, trained at centralized RI training centers, are selected from over 25 villages in North Darfur and once trained, return to their home villages to work as technical advisors and resources for their own communities.  RI currently operates seven animal health care clinics in the region to deliver primary livestock health care including preventative and curative services including vaccination campaigns, deworming, and disease treatment to over 120,000 animals per year.</narrative>
  </description>
